<LP>
   A federal appeals court panel in Chicago cleared the way
for 3,000 Trans World Airlines Inc. employees to collect what
their lawyers say could be "tens of millions of dollars" in
back pay and damages stemming from their termination by the
air carrier after a three-month strike in early 1986.
   TWA violated a Labor Department regulation when, after it
fired the employees, it refused to notify them immediately of
their eligibility for preferred hiring status by other
airlines, the court said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The notification, known as a "designated rights letter,"
was an administrative vehicle used by the department to
implement the Employee Protection Program of the Airline
Deregulation Act of 1978. The employee-protection provided by
the act expired in 1988.
   With the letter, employees could have received
preferential treatment over other candidates for jobs with
other airline companies. TWA didn't send the notification
letter until February 1987.
   Each flight attendant will seek an average of two years'
back pay, to cover the period from May 17, 1986 -- when they
ended the strike and offered to return to work -- till they
were rehired by TWA.
   The Seventh U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, affirming a
lower court ruling that found TWA liable, remanded the case
to the trial court for a hearing on damages.
   An attorney for TWA, which is based in Mount Kisco, N.Y.,
said the company was reviewing the decision.
