   PARENT INDUSTRIES pleads guilty to racketeering in weapons
case.
   Parent Industries Inc., a holding company owned by James
H. Guerin, filed the plea in federal court in Philadelphia
yesterday, a month after federal prosecutors charged that the
company participated in a scheme to create more than $1
billion in phony weapons contracts.
   Mr. Guerin, who has not been charged with a crime, was the
creator of International Signal &amp; Control Corp., a global
weapons conglomerate based in Lancaster, Pa., that he started
in 1971 as a backyard industry.
   Parent, the holding company for all of Mr. Guerin's
assets, pleaded guilty to padding and falsifying weapons
contracts to inflate the value of International Signal &amp;
Control prior to its sale in 1987 to Ferranti International
PLC, Britain's third-largest defense contractor, for $670
million.
   Under the terms of the agreement, Parent will forfeit at
least $4 million and pay an additional $2.4 million in fines.
Mr. Guerin remains under investigation.
   In a plea memorandum filed by federal prosecutors, Mr.
Guerin is alleged to have "directed the financial fraud." His
attorney in Philadelphia, Joseph A. Tate, said Mr. Guerin and
Parent are cooperating with prosecutors.
