   DENTISTS ARE CONVICTED in unusual price-fixing case.
   Three dentists were convicted in Tucson, Ariz., on charges
of conspiring to raise and fix fee amounts paid by their
patients, the Justice Department said. The case involved the
first criminal antitrust indictments and convictions of
medical practitioners in 50 years, according to Robert Bloch,
the prosecutor who supervised the case.
   The government in recent years has focused increased
attention on alleged antitrust violations in health care.
Previous cases have involved civil infractions related to
such things as hospital mergers. More criminal charges could
emerge from federal grand jury investigations under way in
Boston and in Savannah, Ga.
   The dentists in the Tucson case were found guilty of
conspiring to raise "co-payment" fees charged to members of
four prepaid dental plans. Co-payments are the extra amounts
that plan members must pay for certain non-routine
procedures, such as root-canal work.
   Convicted Sept. 20 in Tucson were Aaron Alston, Ronald
Walker and Richard Meyer. The dentists couldn't be reached
for comment. Stephen Weiss, Dr. Alston's lawyer, said a
motion has been filed requesting the judge to reverse the
jury's verdict "for lack of sufficient evidence." If the
motion is rejected, as typically happens, the three dentists
"in all likelihood would appeal," the lawyer added.
   Mr. Bloch said that the three men convicted were the
central figures in a conspiracy involving more than 30
dentists and affecting 80,000 dental-plan members. The price
collusion began as early as May 1987 and continued until
February of this year, according to the government.
   The defendants face possible prison terms of as much as
three years each, as well as individual fines of hundreds of
thousands of dollars. Sentencing is scheduled for Dec. 17.
