   FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION official passes through revolving
door.
   Terry Calvani, a commissioner for seven years at the FTC
who briefly served as acting chairman during the mid-1980s,
will become a partner in the Washington law office of San
Francisco-based Pillsbury, Madison &amp; Sutro.
   Mr. Calvani, whose term expires today, will begin work at
the 40-lawyer office tomorrow. An expert on antitrust issues,
Mr. Calvani said that he will advise clients on antitrust
matters pending at the FTC, and that he expects to represent
clients before the commission as soon as the law will allow.
In most instances, federal officials are permitted to
represent clients before their former agencies after a
one-year grace period.
   The White House said last week it would nominate Roscoe
Burton Starek, White House deputy director for personnel, to
fill Mr. Calvani's seat. Before going to the White House, the
42-year-old Mr. Starek worked for seven years in various
capacities at the State Department, including the post of
deputy assistant secretary for policy and counterterrorism.
He also held several legal positions on Capitol Hill in the
1970s.
   The post at the FTC requires Senate confirmation.
